{
  "What does the y-axis represent on a velocity-time graph?": "",
  "The velocity of the object": "",
  "The position of the object": "",
  "The acceleration of the object": "",
  "The total distance traveled": "",
  "On a velocity-time graph, the y-axis shows the velocity of the object at each moment. The x-axis shows time. This lets us see how fast the object is moving at any point during its journey.": "",
  "What does a horizontal line on a velocity-time graph indicate about the object's motion?": "",
  "The object is speeding up steadily": "",
  "The object is moving at constant velocity": "",
  "The object is slowing down steadily": "",
  "The object is completely at rest": "",
  "A horizontal (flat) line on a velocity-time graph means the velocity is not changing. The object moves at a constant velocity with zero acceleration. A flat line at zero would mean at rest, but any other flat line means steady motion.": "",
  "What does the slope of a line on a velocity-time graph represent?": "",
  "The total displacement of the object": "",
  "The average speed of the object": "",
  "The direction the object faces": "",
  "The slope of a velocity-time graph equals the rate at which velocity changes, which is acceleration. A steeper slope means greater acceleration, and a negative slope means the object is decelerating.": "",
  "What does the area under a velocity-time graph represent?": "",
  "The average velocity of the object": "",
  "The total force on the object": "",
  "The displacement of the object": "",
  "The area between the velocity-time line and the time axis equals the displacement. For a rectangle (constant velocity), area = velocity x time = displacement. This works for any shape on the graph.": "",
  "On a velocity-time graph, what does a straight line with a positive slope indicate?": "",
  "Constant positive acceleration": "",
  "Decreasing positive velocity": "",
  "Constant negative acceleration": "",
  "No acceleration at all": "",
  "A straight line with a positive slope on a v-t graph means the velocity is increasing at a steady rate. This is uniform positive acceleration. The steeper the line, the greater the acceleration.": "",
  "What does a line sloping downward on a velocity-time graph tell you?": "",
  "The object is gaining speed over time": "",
  "The object is moving at a steady pace": "",
  "The object is slowing down over time": "",
  "The object is not moving at all": "",
  "A downward-sloping line means velocity is decreasing over time. The object is decelerating (slowing down). If the line crosses zero, the object stops and may reverse direction.": "",
  "On a velocity-time graph, a steeper slope compared to a gentler slope means what?": "",
  "The object has a lower velocity": "",
  "The object has a greater acceleration": "",
  "The object covers less total distance": "",
  "The object has exactly zero acceleration": "",
  "Since slope on a velocity-time graph equals acceleration, a steeper slope means the velocity is changing more rapidly. A steep upward slope is large acceleration; a gentle slope is small acceleration.": "",
  "What are the standard units shown on the axes of a velocity-time graph?": "",
  "Meters on the y-axis and kilograms on the x-axis": "",
  "Newtons on the y-axis and seconds on the x-axis": "",
  "Meters per second on the y-axis and meters on x-axis": "",
  "Meters per second on the y-axis and seconds on x-axis": "",
  "A velocity-time graph plots velocity (m/s) on the y-axis against time (s) on the x-axis. These are the standard SI units used for this type of motion graph.": "",
  "On a velocity-time graph, what does a line sitting at zero velocity for a period of time mean?": "",
  "The object is completely at rest during that time": "",
  "The object is accelerating very quickly upward": "",
  "The object is traveling at maximum possible speed": "",
  "The object is moving at a constant slow speed": "",
  "If the line on a velocity-time graph stays at zero, the object has zero velocity and is not moving. It is completely at rest for that entire time interval.": "",
  "When a velocity-time graph line crosses the zero velocity line, what happens to the object?": "",
  "The object starts to accelerate faster": "",
  "The object changes its direction of motion": "",
  "The object comes to a permanent stop": "",
  "The object doubles its current speed": "",
  "When the line crosses zero velocity on a v-t graph, the object momentarily stops and then reverses direction. Positive velocity becomes negative, meaning the object now moves in the opposite direction.": "",
  "What is a velocity-time graph?": "",
  "A table listing speed values at different locations": "",
  "A diagram showing forces acting on an object": "",
  "A graph that plots an object's velocity against time": "",
  "A chart comparing distance to total mass": "",
  "A velocity-time graph (v-t graph) is a visual tool that plots an object's velocity on the y-axis against time on the x-axis. It shows how the speed and direction of an object change over a period of time.": "",
  "What does the term 'acceleration' mean on a velocity-time graph?": "",
  "The total distance covered by an object over time": "",
  "The object's position at a single instant in time": "",
  "The weight of the moving object at any moment": "",
  "The rate at which velocity changes, shown by slope": "",
  "Acceleration is the rate of change of velocity. On a velocity-time graph, it is represented by the slope of the line. A positive slope means speeding up, a negative slope means slowing down, and zero slope means constant velocity.": "",
  "What does 'deceleration' mean?": "",
  "Motion in a perfectly circular path": "",
  "A decrease in an object's velocity over time": "",
  "An increase in velocity over a time period": "",
  "Maintaining the exact same speed always": "",
  "Deceleration means the object is slowing down, so its velocity is decreasing over time. On a velocity-time graph, deceleration appears as a line with a negative slope going downward.": "",
  "What does 'constant velocity' mean?": "",
  "Speed and direction remain the same over time": "",
  "Speed increases at a steady and uniform rate": "",
  "The object frequently changes its direction": "",
  "The object is not moving in any direction": "",
  "Constant velocity means both the speed and direction of an object stay the same. On a velocity-time graph, this appears as a flat horizontal line because the velocity does not change.": "",
  "What does a negative velocity value mean on a velocity-time graph?": "",
  "The object has completely stopped moving": "",
  "The object is getting heavier over time": "",
  "The object is accelerating very rapidly": "",
  "The object is moving in the opposite direction": "",
  "A negative velocity on a v-t graph means the object is moving in the direction opposite to what was defined as positive. It does not mean the object is stopped; it simply means it is traveling the other way.": "",
  "What does 'uniform acceleration' mean?": "",
  "The object moves in a circular path always": "",
  "Velocity stays constant without any changes": "",
  "Velocity changes by equal amounts in equal times": "",
  "The object stops and then reverses itself": "",
  "Uniform acceleration means the velocity changes at a constant rate. On a velocity-time graph, uniform acceleration appears as a straight line because the velocity increases or decreases by the same amount every second.": "",
  "What is meant by 'displacement' when reading a velocity-time graph?": "",
  "The total area between the line and the time axis": "",
  "The highest point reached on the velocity axis": "",
  "The slope of the line at any particular point": "",
  "The difference between the start and end time": "",
  "Displacement is the change in position of an object. On a velocity-time graph, displacement equals the area between the line and the time axis. Areas above the axis count as positive, and areas below count as negative.": "",
  "What does 'instantaneous velocity' mean on a velocity-time graph?": "",
  "The average of all velocity values on the graph": "",
  "The velocity at one specific moment shown on the graph": "",
  "The final velocity minus the initial velocity value": "",
  "The maximum velocity the object can ever reach": "",
  "Instantaneous velocity is the velocity of an object at one specific point in time. On a velocity-time graph, you can read it directly by finding the value on the y-axis at any chosen time on the x-axis.": "",
  "What does 'non-uniform acceleration' mean?": "",
  "The velocity stays exactly the same over time": "",
  "The velocity increases by equal amounts each second": "",
  "The object is completely stationary at all times": "",
  "The acceleration changes, shown as a curved line": "",
  "Non-uniform acceleration means the rate of velocity change is itself changing. On a v-t graph, this appears as a curved line rather than a straight one, because the slope is different at different points.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'slope' on a velocity-time graph?": "",
  "The total distance an object has traveled": "",
  "The mass of the object that is in motion": "",
  "The steepness of the line showing how fast velocity changes": "",
  "The point where the line crosses the y-axis": "",
  "The slope of a line is its steepness, calculated as rise over run. On a velocity-time graph, the slope equals the change in velocity divided by the change in time, which is the definition of acceleration.": "",
  "A car starts from rest and reaches 20 m/s in 4 seconds, shown as a straight line on a v-t graph. What is its acceleration?": "",
  "80 m/s squared": "",
  "5 m/s squared": "",
  "24 m/s squared": "",
  "16 m/s squared": "",
  "Acceleration equals the slope of the v-t graph: change in velocity divided by change in time. Here, acceleration = (20 - 0) / (4 - 0) = 20/4 = 5 m/s squared.": "",
  "A train's v-t graph shows a horizontal line at 30 m/s for 10 seconds. How far did the train travel during that time?": "",
  "300 meters": "",
  "150 meters": "",
  "400 meters": "",
  "200 meters": "",
  "The area under a v-t graph equals displacement. For a horizontal line at 30 m/s over 10 seconds, the area is a rectangle: 30 m/s x 10 s = 300 meters.": "",
  "A bicycle's v-t graph shows velocity dropping from 15 m/s to 0 m/s in 5 seconds. What is the rate of deceleration?": "",
  "75 m/s squared": "",
  "20 m/s squared": "",
  "10 m/s squared": "",
  "3 m/s squared": "",
  "Deceleration = change in velocity / time = (15 - 0) / 5 = 3 m/s squared. The velocity decreased by 3 m/s every second until the bicycle came to a complete stop.": "",
  "A runner's v-t graph shows 8 m/s for 5 seconds, then 4 m/s for 5 seconds. What is the total displacement?": "",
  "40 meters total": "",
  "20 meters total": "",
  "60 meters total": "",
  "80 meters total": "",
  "Displacement equals the total area under the v-t graph. First section: 8 m/s x 5 s = 40 m. Second section: 4 m/s x 5 s = 20 m. Total displacement = 40 + 20 = 60 meters.": "",
